summary: In 2024, NAIDOC Week will be celebrated under the theme "Keep the Fire Burning! Blak, Loud and Proud!" Organizations across Australia are preparing for this annual event that recognizes the history, culture, and achievements of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander peoples. La Trobe University, Primary Health Network, Mansfield Shire Council, Football Victoria, City of Wagga Wagga, Mirage News, Curtin University, the Government of South Australia, Redlands Coast Today, and Region Riverina are among those announcing plans for NAIDOC Week 2024. These celebrations will include flag-raising ceremonies, artist talks, cultural events, and opportunities for the community to get involved and learn about Indigenous culture and history.

Prime Minister Albanese has since disciplined Payman for her vote, but has indicated that she could be welcomed back into the caucus in the future.

Tragic details have since emerged, including the identification of one of the three deceased women killed in the accident. The highway has been littered with potholes, which a local MP claims may have contributed to the accident. Dozens of people were seriously injured and are receiving medical attention at local hospitals. Authorities are investigating the cause of the crash, and the highway has reopened after extensive delays.
